sql:
SELECT AVG(watch_time) AS average_watch_time_from_rebuffering_videos
FROM video_analytics
WHERE rebuffering_count > 0;

external_knowledge:
- "Best quality video representations" are those where the `is_best` flag is set to 1;
- "Quality rating" is a score given by users on a scale of 1 to 5, where 5 is the highest;
- "Codec" refers to the compression and decompression algorithm used for the video;
- "Bitrate" is the amount of data used per second of video, measured in kbps;
- "Framerate" is the number of frames per second in the video.

- 'watched through the cellular waves' refers to streaming sessions that used a cellular network;
- 'gathered a fleet of more than five sessions' means the video has been streamed more than 5 times;
- 'average speed at which these digital ships sail' refers to the average download speed of the network in Mbps;
- 'calm or turbulent nature of the network's ping' refers to the average ping time of the network in milliseconds;
- 'ranked from the swiftest to the slowest' means the results are ordered by average download speed in descending order.

- 'High quality ratings' refer to ratings greater than 3 on a scale of 1 to 5;
- 'Significant view counts' refer to videos that have been viewed more than 1000 times;
- 'Engaging durations' refer to the average view duration of the video, indicating user engagement;
- 'Most popular videos' are determined by the descending order of view counts.

sql:
SELECT AVG(ssim) 
FROM video_representations 
WHERE is_best = 1;

SELECT COUNT(chunk_id) 
FROM video_chunks 
WHERE rebuffering_duration > 0.0;

SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM quality_metrics 
WHERE vmaf > (SELECT AVG(vmaf) FROM quality_metrics);

external_knowledge:
- 'tech-savvy users' refers to users who have provided feedback with a quality rating greater than 4;
- 'high workload' refers to CPU and memory usage both exceeding 50%;
- 'excellent quality ratings' refers to ratings greater than 4;
- 'more than one such session' means the user has participated in more than one session meeting these criteria.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(video_id) 
FROM video_analytics 
WHERE view_count > (SELECT AVG(view_count) FROM video_analytics);

external_knowledge:
- "total number of views" refers to the sum of all views for each video;
- "average view duration" is the mean duration viewers spend watching each video;
- "total engagement" includes likes, comments, and shares for each video.

sql:
SELECT session_id, cpu_usage, memory_usage
FROM device_analysis
WHERE cpu_usage > 20.0 AND memory_usage < 1500.0;

SELECT video_id, view_count, average_view_duration
FROM video_analytics
WHERE view_count > 1000 AND average_view_duration > 30;

SELECT COUNT(device_id) 
FROM device_analysis
WHERE cpu_usage > 30.0 AND memory_usage > 1000.0 AND battery_level > 50.0;

external_knowledge:
- Popularity is determined by the number of views (`view_count`);
- Viewer engagement is measured by the average view duration (`average_view_duration`) and the average engagement score (`average_engagement`);
- Quality metrics include PSNR, SSIM, MSSSIM, VQM, STRRED, VMAF, and SSIMPlus.

- The best-quality video representations are determined by the highest average PSNR and SSIM values;
- PSNR and SSIM are metrics used to measure the quality of video representations;
- The query ranks the combinations of video ID and codec based on these metrics and selects the top-ranked ones.

- The total duration of streaming sessions is measured in seconds;
- Sessions with a total duration greater than 300 seconds (5 minutes) are considered long sessions;
- User engagement includes metrics such as watch time, rebuffering count, and average engagement;
- The query focuses on user behavior and streaming performance.

sql:
SELECT DISTINCT ss.user_id
FROM streaming_sessions ss
WHERE ss.total_duration > 300;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT network_type) 
FROM network_analysis 
WHERE download_speed > 50 AND upload_speed > 25;

external_knowledge:
- Engagement score is a metric that combines the view count and watch time of a video, adjusted by the average device usage metrics (CPU usage, memory usage, battery level) during the streaming sessions;
- A video is considered to have strong viewer attention if it has more than 100 views and a watch time greater than 3600 seconds (1 hour);
- The engagement score is calculated as (view count * watch time) / (average CPU usage + average memory usage + average battery level).

- "Sailing smoothly for more than 5 minutes" refers to sessions with a total duration greater than 300 seconds;
- "Minimal interruptions" refers to sessions with less than 10 seconds of rebuffering;
- "Combined visual and structural quality" is calculated as the average of PSNR (Peak Signal-to-Noise Ratio) and SSIM (Structural Similarity Index).

- Visual sharpness (bitrate) refers to the clarity of the video, with higher bitrates providing better quality;
- Smoothness (framerate) refers to the smoothness of the video playback, with higher framerates providing smoother video;
- Robust chunks are video segments that have high bitrate and duration, ensuring better quality and longer playtime;
- Rebuffering duration is the time a video pauses to load more data, with lower values indicating a smoother streaming experience.

- "top 10 most viewed" refers to videos with the highest `view_count`;
- "top 10 most watched" refers to videos with the highest `watch_time`;
- "most engaged user" refers to the user with the highest `watch_time` for each video.

- 'Moderate' CPU usage is considered to be between 20 and 50;
- 'Fast' download speed is defined as greater than 50 Mbps;
- 'Good' quality rating is defined as greater than 3 on a scale of 1 to 5.
